X|via=eLibrary}}\n*Alkire, Ti; Rosen, Rosen (July 2010). ''Romance Languages: A Historical Introduction''. New York: Cambridge University Press. ISBN <bdi>9780521717847</bdi>.\n*{{Cite book|last=Vincent|first=Nigel|title=Early and Late Latin: Continuity or Change?|last2=Adams|first2=J. N.|last3=Maltby|first3=Robert|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-107-13225-2|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Roger|title=Late Latin and Early Romance in Spain and Carolingian France|publisher=Francis Cairns|year=1982|isbn=0-905205-12-X|location=Liverpool|pages=}}\n[[Category:Latin]]\n[[Category:Linguistics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Proto-Romance''' is the [[Comparative method|comparatively]] [[Linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] ancestor of all [[Romance languages|Romance Languages]]. It reflects a late variety of [[Latin]], one of the [[Italic languages|Italic Languages]] in the broader [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] family.\n\nExceptionally in the field of [[Comparative linguistics|Comparative Linguistics]], specialists in Proto-Romance have at their disposal an abundant corpus of their [[Proto-language|proto language]] in its written register- that is to say, Latin. This has however had the drawback of leading many scholars to rely excessively on the written record in lieu of reconstructing Proto-Romance proper.<ref>Dworkin (2016), p. 2</ref> \n\nAs conceived in the Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman, Proto-Romance most closely reflects Latin as spoken around the sixth century AD.<ref>Kramer (2014), p. 295</ref>\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Monophthongs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|Close]]\n|{{IPA link|i}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]]\n|[[Near-close near-front unrounded vowel|\u026a]]\n|\n|[[Near-close back rounded vowel|\u028a]]\n|-\n![[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|e}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|o}}\n|-\n![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|\u025b}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u0254}}\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Open]]\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u00e4|a}}\n|\n|}\n\n* The open-mid vowels /\u025b, \u0254/ merge with /e, o/ in all unstressed contexts.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 73\u20136</ref><ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 78</ref>\n\n* A further reduction is observed in intertonic syllables where /i, u/ merge with /\u026a, \u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 78\u201381</ref>\n\n* Vowels are lengthened allophonically in stressed open syllables,<ref>Loporcaro (2015), pp. 25\u201330</ref> although not /\u026a/ or /\u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 69</ref>\n\n* /i, u/ become [j, w] between a consonant and following vowel. [j] then triggers [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]], e.g. /basi\u00e1re/ [bas\u02b2\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref>\n\n=== Diphthong ===\nOnly one diphthong can be reconstructed for Proto-Romance, namely /aw/. It can be found in both stressed and unstressed positions.<ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 84</ref> Its phonemic status is however debatable, as it could also be simply regarded as a sequence of /a/ and /u/.<ref>Xavier, p. 81</ref>\n\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! colspan=\"2\" |Coronal\n! colspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! colspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n|-\n!Nasal\n|\n|m\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Occlusive\n|p\n|b\n|t\n|d\n|k\n|g\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |j\n|-\n!Fricative\n|f\n|\u03b2\n|s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Labialized\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|k\u02b7\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Vibrant\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |r\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Lateral\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |l\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n* When palatalized /t, k, n, l/ become [ts\u02b2, c, \u0272, \u028e].<ref name=\"Xavier\" /><ref>Zampaulo (2019), pp. 50, 78, 94</ref>\n* Intervocalic [c, \u0272, \u028e] regularly [[Gemination|geminate]].<ref name=\"Xavier\">Xavier (2014), pp. 92\u2013115</ref> [ts\u02b2] does so only sporadically.<ref>Wilkin (1926), pp. 11\u201314</ref>\n*Words beginning with /sC/ undergo [[Prothesis (linguistics)|prosthesis]], e.g. /st\u00e1re/ [\u026ast\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee], unless preceded by a vowel.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 125\u20136</ref><ref>Hall (1976), p. 128</ref>\n* It is debated whether /k\u02b7/ is its own phoneme or merely an allophone of /ku/ before vowels.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 100</ref>\n* There is some evidence that /f/ could have been bilabial, but a labiodental is still more likely.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 38</ref>\n* /b, d, g/ fricativize to [\u03b2, \u00f0, \u0263] between vowels or in contact with /r/ and /l/.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 48</ref>\n* Intervocalic /di, gi/ do not occur, these having previously reduced to /j/.<ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 87</ref><ref>Xavier (2016), p. 43</ref>\n*The rhotic may have been [\u027e~r], as in Spanish or Catalan.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 113</ref>\n*Word-initial /j/ underwent fortition to [\u025f].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 84</ref>\n* /ll/ had a retroflex realization: [\u026d\u026d].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 115</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 164</ref>\n* /gn/ fricativizes to [\u0263n].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 95</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 80</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n\n=== Nouns ===\nProto-Romance nouns had three cases: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], and a combined [[Genitive case|genitive]]-[[Dative case|dative]] which was only used in reference to humans.<ref>De Dardel & Gaenge (1992), p. 104</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Class\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028e\u028as\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028ei\n|m\u00e1tr\u026as''{{efn|De Dardel hesitates to posit this form, giving ''m\u00e1tre'' as a possible alternative. Likewise ''p\u00e1tr\u026as~p\u00e1tre''.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tr\u026as\n|p\u00e1tri\n|-\n!Accusative\n|f\u00e9m\u026anas\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eu''{{efn|For final -u versus -\u028as, see Xavier (2014), p. 78.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eos\n|m\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tres\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|fem\u026an\u00f3ru''{{efn|Unlike De Dardel, Hall (1976, p. 18) has -''aru'' as the feminine ending, as it was in Classical Latin. On the next page, however, he admits that the evidence for it is flimsy.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eo\n|fi\u028e\u028e\u00f3ru\n|m\u00e1tri\n|matr\u00f3ru\n|p\u00e1tri\n|patr\u00f3ru\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |woman\n| colspan=\"2\" |son\n| colspan=\"2\" |mother\n| colspan=\"2\" |father\n|}\n\nSeveral Class III nouns had inflections that differed by syllable count or stress position.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 28</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |singular\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u0254\u0301mo\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|p\u00e1stor\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|s\u0254\u0301ror\n|-\n!Accusative\n|\u0254\u0301m\u026ane\n|past\u00f3re\n|sor\u00f3re\n|-\n!Translation\n|man\n|pastor\n|sister\n|}\nA few Class II nouns were pluralized with -''a'' or ''-ora,'' these originally having been neuter in Classical Latin. Though their singular was masculine, the plural was treated as feminine.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 23\u20134, 29\u201330.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Noun''{{efn|Forms given in the accusative.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2u\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2a\n|braccu\n|bracca\n|t\u025b\u0301mp\u028as\n|t\u025b\u0301mpora\n|p\u025b\u0301kt\u028as\n|p\u025b\u0301ktora\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |egg\n| colspan=\"2\" |arm\n| colspan=\"2\" |time\n| colspan=\"2\" |chest\n|}\nThe plural was often reanalyzed as a feminine singular, resulting in gender shifts.<ref>Akire & Rosen (2010), pp. 193\u20134</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Original noun\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eu\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|k\u0254\u0301rnu\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nu\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|-\n!Fem. variant\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eas\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|k\u0254\u0301rnas\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nas\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |leaf\n| colspan=\"2\" |horn\n| colspan=\"2\" |firewood\n|}\nSuch a trend had already begun in Classical Latin; for example the feminine noun ''opera'' was formed from the plural of neuter ''opus.''\n\n=== Adjectives ===\n\n==== Absolute ====\nBroadly speaking, these decline as nouns do.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Gender\n| colspan=\"2\" |feminine\n| colspan=\"2\" |masculine\n| colspan=\"2\" |either\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bl\u00e1nd\u028as\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|d\u028a\u0301lk\u026as\n| rowspan=\"2\" |d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Accusative\n|bl\u00e1ndas\n|bl\u00e1ndu\n|bl\u00e1ndos\n|d\u028a\u0301lke\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|d\u028a\u0301lki\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |sweet\n|}\n\n==== Comparative ====\nWhile the original Latin ending ''-(i)or'' still existed, it was only used in a limited number of adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 32, 119-20</ref><ref>Maltby (2016), p. 340</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|m\u025b\u0301\u028e\u028eor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|p\u025b\u0301jor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |pej\u00f3res\n|m\u00e1jor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026a\u0301nor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Accusative\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3re\n|pej\u00f3re\n|maj\u00f3re\n|m\u026an\u00f3re\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3ri\n| -\n|pej\u00f3ri\n| -\n|maj\u00f3ri\n|  -\n|m\u026an\u00f3ri\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |better\n| colspan=\"2\" |worse\n| colspan=\"2\" |larger\n| colspan=\"2\" |smaller\n|}\nThe typical way to form a comparative was to add either ''pl\u00fas'' or ''m\u00e1is'' (meaning 'more') to an absolute adjective, which had been done sporadically in Classical Latin as well.<ref>Maltby (2016), pp. 340\u20135.</ref>\n\n==== Superlative ====\nNo dedicated ending existed to express the superlative. A variety of alternatives were used instead, such as an intensifying adverb (m\u028a\u0301ltu, b\u025b\u0301ne, etc.) or a comparative.<ref>Bauer (2016), pp. 340, 359</ref>\n\n==== Possessive ====\n\nShown here in the feminine singular.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 122</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!\n!First person\n!Second person\n!Third person\n|-\n!singular\n|m\u025b\u0301a\n|t\u028a\u0301a\n|s\u028a\u0301a\n|-\n!plural\n|n\u0254\u0301stra\n|\u03b2\u0254\u0301stra\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|}\n\n=== Pronouns ===\n\n==== Personal ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'you', 'me', etc.<ref>De Dardel & W\u00fcest (1993), p. 43</ref><ref name=\"Hall\">Hall (1983), p. 39</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Person\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u025b\u0301o''{{efn|On the cited page, Hall has this as ''ego''. However ''eo'' is found in Hall (1976), p. 216|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |n\u00f3s\n|t\u00fa\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\u03b2\u00f3s\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301lle\n| colspan=\"2\" |\u026a\u0301lli\n|-\n!Accusative\n|m\u00e9, m\u00e9ne\n|t\u00e9, t\u00e9ne\n|\u026a\u0301llas\n|\u026a\u0301llu\n|\u026a\u0301llos\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|m\u00ed, m\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|n\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|t\u00ed, t\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|\u03b2\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|\u026all\u00e9i\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|\u026all\u00fai\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|}\n\n==== Interrogative ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'who' and 'what'.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 42\u201343</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Animacy\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Animate\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Inanimate\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| colspan=\"2\" |ku\u00ed\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u026a\u0301d\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Accusative\n|ku\u025b\u0301ne\n|ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\n\nProto Romance verbs belong to three main classes, each of which is characterized by a different [[thematic vowel]]. Their conjugations are built on three stems and involve various combinations of mood, aspect, and tense.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 47\u201350</ref> Only one chart is shown below; the rest will be explained in a separate article.\n\n==== Present indicative ====\nThis could also connote the near future.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 52\u20136</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |First person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Translation\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Class I\n|k\u00e1nto\n|kant\u00e1m\u028as\n|k\u00e1ntas\n|kant\u00e1t\u026as\n|k\u00e1ntat\n|k\u00e1ntant\n|sing\n|-\n!Class II\n|d\u0254\u0301rmo\n|dorm\u00edm\u028as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026as\n|d\u0254rm\u00edt\u026as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026at\n|d\u0254\u0301rment<br>~d\u0254\u0301rm\u028ant\n|sleep\n|-\n!Class III\n|b\u00e1tto\n|batt\u00e9m\u028as\n|b\u00e1ttes\n|batt\u00e9t\u026as\n|b\u00e1ttet\n|b\u00e1ttent\n|beat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Irregular\n|s\u028a\u0301n\n|s\u028a\u0301m\u028as\n|\u025b\u0301s\n|\u025b\u0301st\u026as~s\u025b\u0301t\u026as~s\u028a\u0301t\u026as\n|\u025b\u0301st\n|s\u028a\u0301nt\n|am/are/is\n|-\n|\u00e1jo\n|a\u03b2\u00e9m\u028as\n|\u00e1s\n|a\u03b2\u00e9t\u026as\n|\u00e1t\n|\u00e1nt~\u00e1unt\n|have/has\n|}\n\n==== Participles ====\nOf these there were only two: a present active and a preterite passive. They declined like adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 122\u20133</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Present Active\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Preterite Passive\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n|-\n!Class I\n|am\u00e1nte\n|(is) adoring\n|am\u00e1ta\n|(was) adored\n|-\n!Class II\n|fin\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) finishing\n|fin\u00edta\n|(was) finished\n|-\n!Class III\n|a\u03b2\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) possessing\n|a\u03b2\u00fata\n|(was) possessed\n|}\n== Relation to written Latin ==\nContrary to the traditional view, Wright argues that there was no distinction between Latin and Romance prior to the ninth century, the former being only a written representation of the latter. For instance in ninth-century Spain \u27e8saeculum\u27e9 was simply the correct way to spell [sjeglo], meaning 'century'. The writer would not have actually said [s\u025bkulum] any more than a modern English speaker would pronounce \u27e8knight\u27e9 as *[kn\u026axt].<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 44\u201350</ref> \n\n[[Ecclesiastical Latin]], in its spoken form, was created later during the [[Carolingian Renaissance]]. The British scholar [[Alcuin]], tasked by [[Charlemagne]] with improving the standards of Latin writing in France, prescribed a pronunciation based on a fairly literal interpretation of Latin spelling. A word such as \u27e8viridiarium\u27e9 'orchard' now had to be read aloud precisely as it was spelled rather than as [[Old French]] ''vergier.''<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 104\u20137</ref>\n\nThis had the effect of rendering [[Sermon|sermons]] completely unintelligible to the general public, which prompted officials a few years later- at the [[Council of Tours]]- to order them to be rendered ''in rusticam romanam linguam'', 'in plain roman speech', i.e. in Romance.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 118-20</ref> Another issue was that now two types of speech, Romance and Church Latin, had to coexist within one writing system. Within the same century the first attempts were made to devise an orthography specifically for Romance, as can be seen in the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] and the [[Sequence of Saint Eulalia|Canticle of Saint Eulalia]], both written in France. As the Carolingian Reforms spread to other Romance-speaking areas, local scholars devised orthographies for their own varieties of Romance as well.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 122\u201332, 143\u20134</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=2014-11-14|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|editor2-last=Schweickard|editor2-first=Wolfgang|editor3-last=Gouvert|editor3-first=Joannes|editor4-last=Kramer|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110313482|journal=Beihefte zur Zeitschrift f\u00f